  "prompt": "If time slows down as you approach the speed of light, then what time scale is light on?",
  "response": "As an object approaches the speed of light, time dilation occurs according to special relativity. Time dilation means that time appears to slow down for that object relative to an observer at rest. However, for a photon (a particle of light) traveling at the speed of light, the concept of time becomes more complex.\n\nFrom the perspective of a photon, which always travels at the speed of light (\\(c\\)), time does not \"tick\" in the same way as it does for objects with mass. In the frame of reference of a photon, the time it takes to travel from its emission point to its absorption point is effectively zero. This is because, according to special relativity, the proper time (the time experienced by the photon itself) along a null geodesic (the path of a light ray) is zero.\n\nHowever, this does not mean that time stops for the entire universe when light is traveling. Instead, it's a feature of the mathematical framework of relativity: from our perspective as observers with mass, light takes a finite amount of time to travel from one point to another, but from light's perspective, it is instantaneously at its destination.\n\nTo summarize, light does not experience time in the way objects with mass do. From light's perspective, the time scale is effectively zero, but this is a theoretical construct since we can't actually be in the reference frame of a photon to experience this.",
